### Classes in C#

A class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines properties, methods, and events that the created objects will have.

### Class Declaration

```csharp
[accessModifier] class ClassName
{
    // Fields, properties, methods, events
}
```

### Basic Class Example

```csharp
public class Person
{
    // Fields (data)
    private string name;
    private int age;

    // Properties
    public string Name
    {
        get { return name; }
        set { name = value; }
    }

    public int Age
    {
        get { return age; }
        set { age = value; }
    }

    // Methods
    public void Introduce()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"Hi, I'm {name} and I'm {age} years old.");
    }
}
```

### Access Modifiers

| Modifier | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| `public` | Accessible from anywhere |
| `private` | Only within the same class |
| `protected` | Within class and derived classes |
| `internal` | Within the same assembly |
| `protected internal` | Same assembly or derived classes |
| `private protected` | Same assembly AND derived classes |

### Class Members

| Member | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| Fields | Variables that hold data |
| Properties | Expose fields with get/set |
| Methods | Define behavior |
| Constructors | Initialize objects |
| Events | Notifications |
| Indexers | Array-like access |
| Operators | Define operator behavior |

### Static Classes

Cannot be instantiated. Contains only static members:

```csharp
public static class MathHelper
{
    public static double Pi = 3.14159;
    public static int Square(int x) => x * x;
}
```

### Partial Classes

Split a class across multiple files:

```csharp
// File1.cs
public partial class Employee
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
}

// File2.cs
public partial class Employee
{
    public void Work() => Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is working");
}
```

> **Key Point:** Classes are reference types. When you assign an object to another variable, both reference the same object. Use the `new` keyword to create an instance. Follow PascalCase naming convention for class names.

### Auto-Implemented Properties

```csharp
public class Product
{
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }
}
```

codeExample:
using System;

public class Car
{
    public string Make { get; set; }
    public string Model { get; set; }
    public int Year { get; set; }

    public void Start()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Year} {Make} {Model} is starting...");
    }
}

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        Car myCar = new Car();
        myCar.Make = "Toyota";
        myCar.Model = "Camry";
        myCar.Year = 2023;
        myCar.Start();
    }
}
